solution:
Let $r = 1994.$  The line joining the center $(0,0)$ to $(a,b)$ is perpendicular to the line joining $(2r,2r)$ to $(a,b).$  Hence, the product of their slopes is $-1.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair O, P, T;

O = (0,0);
P = (2,2);
T = ((1 + sqrt(7))/4,(1 - sqrt(7))/4);

draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw(O--P--T--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(O,T,P,5));

dot("$(0,0)$", O, W);
dot("$(2r,2r)$", P, NE);
dot("$(a,b)$", T, E);
[/asy]

This gives us the equation
\[\frac{2r - b}{2r - a} \cdot \frac{b}{a} = -1.\]Then $b(2r - b) = -a(2r - a),$ which expands as $2br - b^2 = -2ar + a^2.$  Then $2ar + 2br = a^2 + b^2 = r^2,$ so
\[a + b = \frac{r^2}{2r} = \frac{r}{2} = \boxed{997}.\]

For any $x$ and $y$, $(x+y)(x-y)=x^2-y^2+xy-xy=x^2-y^2$, so \begin{align*}
\left( \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} \right) \left( \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} \right)&=\left(\frac12\right)^2-\left(\frac13\right)^2\\
&=\frac14-\frac19\\
&=\frac{9}{36}-\frac{4}{36}\\
&=\boxed{\frac{5}{36}}
\end{align*}

